metadata.name: Megalopolis #291

Abstract artwork that generates urban-like structures viewed from the sky.

metadata.name: Rococo #113
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 150 · 100 · 70 · 50 · 40 · 35 every 8 minutes. Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Nature’s wild flourish and untamed growth wondrously represent the exacting function of beauty — a function that is at once useful and infinitely creative. Perhaps nowhere is this delicate symbiosis better observed than in the flower, wherein a pure balance of physical fundamentals exists beneath ornate patterns and elaborate aesthetics.

Amongst the layers of undulating, vividly colored petals, attention-grabbing stigma and stamen, and lusciously decorative features, nature’s organic abundance and disorder disguises its masterful propensity for precision. Each of the flower’s components evolve through unpredictable interactions with an unwieldy natural environment, creating spectacular adaptations that emerge from the tension between what attracts.

Rococo painters appreciated the organic fluidity found in flowers and vegetal forms, using their joyful abundance to depict a break from the rigid and stoic period the artists hoped to leave behind. They sought to reframe perfection away from predictability and toward compositions as surprising as the natural world around them.

Thus, ‘Rococo’ is a generative distortion of an old tradition: a digital painting created entirely with code that interprets and processes the natural world’s dichotomies. This painting algorithm builds upon natural structures while melding and moving their colors beyond form, growing randomly organic iterations that are as perfect as they are imperfect.

Created by Ori Ben-Shabat & Ronen Tanchum @Phenomenalabs
Creative contributions from Tender @tender_art

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

Technical Details:

- Mobile/GPU Intensive
- Press “s” to save a .png of the artwork in live view
- Press “p” to render a high res output + press “s” to save a printable .png

metadata.name: Elevation #241
metadata.description:
There’s so much more to our world than what we are able to perceive, let alone understand. Will we ever be able to even fully understand ourselves?

–

Elevation is a series of 320 generative elevation drawings of imaginary structures. It is a reminder of the limits of our consciousness, and an ode to the manifold nuances that lie beyond what we can perceive, beyond what we even can imagine.

As a generative artist, I aim to elevate my own consciousness with the help of the machine. I welcome algorithms and randomness into the creation of my works, taking full control, and intentionally giving it away, always seeking to expand my imagination. For as humans alone, we remain limited to our own edifice of thought, and often fail to free ourselves from the visible, mundane world.

Both are present in Elevation: the visible and the imaginary, the mundane and the transcendent, the solid and the fragile. Where an architect’s elevation drawing marks the transition from the thought world into the visible world, Elevation remains in-between, depicting both the idea of an imaginary structure, and the structure itself.

–

Elevation is intended for print. All holders of an Elevation NFT will be able to order the corresponding signed print in the respective paper format via andreasrau.eu/elevation. Press [s] to save the image as displayed or [p] to generate a print-ready PNG image at 300 dpi. This might take a while, depending on paper format and your hardware.

–

Elevation
p5.js, glsl, html, css
Andreas Rau, 2022

metadata.name: Ichigo #91
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (苺/ いちご), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Artifice #240
metadata.description:
This series is is about playful obfuscation.

The fxtext article linked on the main profect goes more in-depth into what is meant by that, as well as the events that led to this collection.

5640 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries. Palettes make up a third of the code.

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (3000 × 3600)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 9000 ×10600 (Chrome only, and may take a moment)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save a png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: Udnē #501
metadata.description:
Udnē is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Performance in Code: Deciphering Value in Generative Art, Art Basel Miami Beach, 2022.

Udnē is a collection of asymmetric textural compositions. It's a search for creating harmonies and disharmonies by combining 3 colors with 3 unsynchronized mathematical equations. Udnē explores the beauty within triadic compositions while attempting to integrate two contrasting textures by forming instances of non-figurative scenes. The collection is a reflection of integrated and contrasting textures in micro and macro scale that we see in our everyday life environment.

You can press 's' in liveMode to save as 1000x1000px .png.

In liveMode, add '&density=7’ to the end of the URL to render at high resolution (7000x7000px). You can use 5, 7 or 10 for different resolutions. It will automatically download when the rendering is finished. 

Some compositions might take longer to render in low-performance computers. Please be patient and enjoy the process!

As a rare probability there is an intentionally kept glitch.

Made with p5js.
@distcollective, November 2022

metadata.name: Primordial #221
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

metadata.name: The Woodcarver's apprentice #66
metadata.description:
A mix of aesthetics from the Ukiyo-e and Shin-hanga woodblock movements, with modern elements.  

ukiyo-e (浮世絵) = "pictures of the floating world", which peaked in the late 19th century. 
shin-hanga (新版画) = "new prints", from roughly the 1920-1950s. 

Some comparisons between the prints of the Japanese masters and gen-art: 

* The number of prints. Based on how well a piece was received, the publisher could decide to produce more copies, usually in batches of 200. Compare this to limiting the edition size on fx(hash). The initial prints would have sharp lines and accurately coloured areas. Very popular prints with thousands of impressions would slowly degrade the blocks, leaving final prints with worn-out linework and colours that weren't true to originals.  

* Woodblock prints were actually a collab between the artist, the wood carver, and the printer. In many cases only the artist and publisher were recognized on the final prints. It was usually the publisher who owned the woodblock, not the artist. Often the artist was considered a worker, contracted at the request of the publisher or patrons funding the project. Compare this to the NFT space, where ownership is carved onto the blockchain, and artists have freedom to create whatever they wish. 

* Copyminters.... Similar to the NFT world, fake publishers sprang up from time to time, who would reproduce famous prints. Enji Takamizawa was one such counterfeiter, who was able to skilfully produce woodblocks replicating originals down to the wood grain! 

* While fine-quality woodblock prints from the Edo era command huge auction prices today, they were in reality affordable art for the regular people of their time. NFTs are similar in this light, where we can enjoy pieces at home rather than say, visiting galleries or museums of unattainable art. 



Additional querystring params (use when viewing in a separate window) 

* fullsize=true (33 megapixel output) 
* colourcorrect=false 
* grain=false 
* border=false 



Licenses included in source. Relying on: 

* PIXIJS for drawing 
* JSTS for geometry functions 
* chromajs for colour functions 
* noise and gaussian helpers from p5js

metadata.name: Hydro Gen #5
metadata.description:
Against the backdrop of texts about valuing water, Hydro Gen charts the ecological devastation and eventual revival of the Tisza river following what has been called one of the gravest environmental disasters in central Europe since Chernobyl.

Nature and humans here are bound within a single frame — havoc in the ecological system activates the breakdown of meaning in the human signifying system of language, but hidden in the wave of ecological disaster is a (re)generative love poem to water that bears witness to its multifaceted beauty and power. A second poem is generated as a soundtrack based on the displayed background text.

- - - - - CLICK TO START SOUND - - - - -

Hydro Gen is a collaborative work conceptualized and developed over the course of one week as part of NFT DEB Generative Dimensions 2022 Hackathon and Conference.

Kalen Iwamoto, lead artist, director

Vitalii Shumanskyi, lead programmer

Nayven Vignette, audio programmer

Tamás Béke, data analysis and visualization

metadata.name: CHIP #76
metadata.description:
A CHIP is being constructed by using two brushes that are painting on the board through deterministic noise, and then turned squared and pixelated and blended into each other, with colours selected from 21 different colour schemes. How many iterations, and the speed and size of the added parts determines the final composition. 

You can stop the iterations by pressing S, and download the current composition by hitting D, and restart/reload the iterations by pressing R.

Notes
The thumbnail generation takes a while and the render/iterations in non-GPU browser can be quite slow. Chrome/Firefox recommended.

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #197
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to “lush, green” and Brut means “dry, raw, or unrefined.”

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth… but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-Borgström, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‘S’ : save as png (2376 × 3360)
’V’ : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‘g=n’ : no grain
‘g=p’ : paper grain
‘h=t’ : high resolution mode, 5940 × 8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append “&g=p&h=t” to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: a fortiori #67
metadata.description:
Energy is everywhere: it’s moving our bodies, buzzing around a city, growing the universe, and connecting everything within it. Perhaps the strongest symbol humans use for energy – for ideas, life, and the various incarnations of power – is light itself. 

For centuries, each form of art has tried to capture the energetic luminescence of a bright light, a warm glow, a spark... if we could only draw with its pure brilliance! From Caravaggio’s diagonal beams, to Picasso drawing with light across Gjon Mili’s photographic emulsions… this pursuit persists through obsessive efforts by artists of every media. 

a fortiori seeks to capture this power of light with code, output on the native illumination of modern screens. The visual deconstruction of light and its reassembly into a frozen moment produces the tangible shards of each spark – resulting in a sum of marks that exceeds the value of their individual parts. It’s then the obsessive energy of generative art’s looping and controlled randomness that enable its repeated mark making, of all types, to express the nearly-intangible intensity of light.

What one hand might communicate in drawing, with light or stick or keyboard, 100 hands would therefore say 100 times louder, clearer, and more impactfully. And if one could capture the authentic energy of traveling light in a single image, it stands to reason that 500 of these images will multiply their energy-inducing qualities together, and exponentially grow their collective power. In this idea, the medium is the message – proving the power of the medium, and its ability to generate energy.


--------

TENDER x Thomas Noya
December 2022

Source code is licensed under the GNU Lesser General Public License as published by the Free Software Foundation.

a fortiori was created in p5.js and is optimized for live output in Chrome. Press these keys in live view to control the art and render high resolution versions of any token:

x = pause
y = play
1 = 1000x1000
2-9 = 2000x2000, …, 9000x9000
0 = 10000x10000
t = 12500x12500
f = 15000x15000
s = save PNG

Outputs beyond 10,000 pixels square are dependent on individual computer and browser capabilities. 

10% of all primary and secondary proceeds donated directly to Girls Who Code

◉_◉

metadata.name: EDDY #9
metadata.description:
An eddy is a circular movement of water counter to a main current. It reminds me of innovations in art, like a small countercurrent to the mainstream, surfacing new techniques and aesthetics. 

I hope that EDDY will brighten your days with its playful swirl of colors, inspired by the sea, the sky, the birds, and post-impressionist paintings.

Keyboard Controls:
[F] Fill the window.
[S] Save the current view in live mode as an image (default 1125x1500px).
[1] [2] [4] [6] Change resolution, 1.5K to 9K.
[R] Reverse course.

Made with p5js and shaders.

Created by elsif, 2022.12.

metadata.name: Levitation #107
metadata.description:
Abstract structures floating in space. 

——————

Levitation continues my exploration of Suprematism and Geometric Abstraction. It contains my developments and ideas for the past half a year.
Starting as mostly inspired by Kleine Welten (Small Worlds) series by Wassily Kandinsky, the collection evolved more into Suprematic compositions.

——————

To change the size of an image, open it in live view and add ‘&size=[size (6200 max.)]’ to the end of the URL.

Controls:
[Arrow Up / Down] — increase / decrease animation speed.
[R] — skip the animation.
[C] — switch between clean and grainy versions.
[S] — save the image.

Created using p5.js and GLSL.
License: CC BY-NC-SA 4.0.

——————

hrunz. — Nov. 2022.
